1 Binomial distribution.

1.1 Probability Mass Function

We will plot the probability mass function for the binomial distribution Bin(n, p). Note: 1) The values for this random variable are 0, 1, 2, , n. 2) The density plot will have a bar of height P(X=k), at the point k on the x-axis. 3) In the plot include a vertical line at the expected value of Bin(n,p).

Write a function plot_binom, that takes input values: n and p, and returns the density plot of Bin(n,p).

plot_binom_pmf <- function(n, p) {
  x <- 0:n
  binomvals <- dbinom(x, size = n, prob = p)
  plot(x, binomvals, type = "h", lwd = 5,
       main = paste("Binomial density for", p),
       xlab = "x", ylab = "P(X=x)")
  abline(v = n * p, col = 'red', lwd = 4)  
}

Fix n = 40. Compute plots of the pmf for the following values of p: 0.05, 0.1, 0.4, 0.6, 0.9, 0.95. Have all the plots on the same frame.

1.2 Cumulative Distribution Functions

Write a function to plot the cumulative distribution function of the Binomial random variable, call it plot_binom_cdf.

plot_binom_cdf <- function(n = 40) {
  p_values <- c(0.05, 0.1, 0.4, 0.6, 0.9, 0.95)  
  x <- 0:n  
  colors <- rainbow(length(p_values))  

  plot(x, pbinom(x, size = n, prob = p_values[1]), type = "s", lwd = 2,
       col = colors[1], ylim = c(0, 1),
       main = paste("CDF of Binomial Distribution (n =", n, ")"),
       xlab = "x", ylab = "P(X  x)")

  for (i in 2:length(p_values)) {
    lines(x, pbinom(x, size = n, prob = p_values[i]), type = "s", col = colors[i], lwd = 2)
  }
  abline(h = 0.8, col = "red", lty = "dotted", lwd = 2)
  
}

plot_binom_cdf(40)

2 Poisson Distribution.

2.1 Probability Mass Functions

We will plot the mass function for the Poison distribution Pois(mu). Note: 1) The values for this random variable are: 0, 1, 2, 3, . 2) The density plot will have a bar of height P(X=k), at the point k on the x-axis. 3) Since most of the densities will be concentrated at lower values of k, we will fix a large enough value of n, say n = 100, when drawing the density plots. 3) In the plot include a vertical line at the expected value of Pois(mu).

The following function is a first jab at writing a function to plot the pmf of the Poisson Distribution

n <- 100 
plot_pois_pmf <- function(mu){
  x <- 0:n
  pois <- dpois(x, lambda = mu)
  plot(x, pois, type = "h", lwd = 5,
       main = paste("Poisson density: mu = ", mu),
       xlab = "x", ylab = "P(X=x)")
  abline(v = mu, col = 'red', lwd = 4)
}

plot_pois_pmf(5)

2.2 Cumulative Distribution Functions

Write a function plot_pois_cdf that takes input and returns the plot of the cdf of the Pois()Pois().

plot_pois_cdf <- function(mu) {
  x <- 0:ceiling(mu + 3 * sqrt(mu)) 
  
  cdf_vals <- ppois(x, lambda = mu)
  
  plot(x, cdf_vals, type = "s", lwd = 2,
       main = paste("CDF of Pois( =", mu, ")"),
       xlab = "x", ylab = "P(X  x)",
       ylim = c(0, 1))  
  
  abline(h = seq(0, 1, by = 0.1), col = "black", lty = "solid")
}

For the following values of mu compute the plots for the pmf of the Poisson distribution: mu: 0.5, 1, 5, 8, 20, 50. Have all plots on the same frame.

3 Comparing Poison with Binomial

We say two random variables XX and YY are identically distributed if they have the same cumulative distribution functions, that is

FX(u)=FY(u)xRFX(u)=FY(u)xR
We can use the Poisson distribution to approximate the Binomial distribution. Lets visualize it now:

Plot the graphs of the cdf of Binom(n=10,p=0.5)Binom(n=10,p=0.5) and Pois(=5)Pois(=5) on the same plot.

plot_binom_pois_cdf <- function(n, p, mu) {
  x_binom <- 0:n  #
  cdf_binom <- pbinom(x_binom, size = n, prob = p)  

  x_pois <- 0:ceiling(mu + 3 * sqrt(mu))  
  cdf_pois <- ppois(x_pois, lambda = mu)  


  plot(x_binom, cdf_binom, type = "s", lwd = 2, col = "blue",
       main = paste("CDFs of Binomial and Poisson"),
       xlab = "x", ylab = "P(X  x)", ylim = c(0, 1))

  lines(x_pois, cdf_pois, type = "s", lwd = 2, col = "red")
  
}

plot_binom_pois_cdf(n = 10, p = 0.5, mu = 5)

Do the graphs overlap? Why/Why not? YOUR ANSWER: Yes, this show hows the Poisson distribution can estimate that if the binomial distribution.

Now plot the graphs of the cdf of Binom(n=1000,p=0.005)Binom(n=1000,p=0.005) and Pois(=5)Pois(=5).

plot_binom_pois_cdf(1000, 0.005, 5)

Do the graphs overlap? Why/Why not? YOUR ANSWER: Yes, since it is a larger range to estimate, although it does not overlap at the beginning.

4.2 Varying mean, fixed standard deviation

4.2.1 Plotting Densities

Set =0.4=0.4. For values of given by 1,0.5,0,0.4,0.9,2.5,41,0.5,0,0.4,0.9,2.5,4 plot the densities of N(,)N(,) in the same plot. You might need to choose appropriate limits for the x-axis.

library(ggplot2)

plot_normal_density <- function(mu_values, sigma) {
  x_values <- seq(-3, 5, length.out = 1000)
  
  density_data <- data.frame(
    x = rep(x_values, length(mu_values)),
    mu = rep(mu_values, each = length(x_values)),
    density = unlist(lapply(mu_values, function(mu) dnorm(x_values, mean = mu, sd = sigma)))
  )
  
  # Plot
  ggplot(density_data, aes(x = x, y = density, color = as.factor(mu))) +
    geom_line(size = 1) +
    labs(title = "Density Functios of N(, )", x = "x", y = "Density", color = "") +
    xlim(-3, 5) +  
    ylim(0, 1) +   
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(legend.position = "bottom")
}

mu_values <- c(-1, -0.5, 0, 0.4, 0.9, 2.5, 4)
sigma <- 0.4
plot_normal_density(mu_values, sigma)

5.2 Cummulative Distribution Function

For values of in (0.2,0.5,1,2,8,10)(0.2,0.5,1,2,8,10) plot the graphs of the cumulative distribution function of Exp()Exp() in the same plot. Draw a horizontal line at y=0.8y=0.8.

plot_exp_cdf <- function(lambda_values) {
  x_values <- seq(0, 5, length.out = 1000)

  # Set up the plot
  plot(x_values, pexp(x_values, rate = lambda_values[1]), type = "l", 
       col = "blue", ylim = c(0, 1), 
       xlab = "x", ylab = "CDF", 
       main = "CDF of Exponential Distribution")

  for (lambda in lambda_values[-1]) {
    lines(x_values, pexp(x_values, rate = lambda), col = rainbow(length(lambda_values))[which(lambda_values == lambda)])
  }

  abline(h = 0.8, col = "red", lty = 2)
}

plot_exp_cdf(c(0.2, 0.5, 1, 2, 8, 10))

6.2 =1=1 , varying scales

Set =1=1, vary over 0.2,0.6,1,1.5,20.2,0.6,1,1.5,2. Plot the densities of Gamma(,)Gamma(,) in a single plot.

plot_gamma_density <- function(alpha, beta_values) {
  x <- seq(0, 15, by = 0.01)  
  
  plot(x, dgamma(x, shape = alpha, rate = beta_values[1]), type = "n", 
       xlab = "x", ylab = "Density", 
       main = paste("Gamma Distribution Density for alpha =", alpha),
       ylim = c(0, 1))
  
  for (beta in beta_values) {
    lines(x, dgamma(x, shape = alpha, rate = beta), 
          col = rainbow(length(beta_values))[which(beta_values == beta)], 
          lwd = 2)
  }

}
  beta_values <- c(0.2, 0.6, 1, 1.5, 2)
  plot_gamma_density(1, beta_values)
